In [[electronics]] ([[radio]] in particular), a '''spurious tone''' (also known as an '''interfering tone''', a '''continuous tone''' or a '''spur''') denotes a tone in an [[electronic circuit]] which interferes with a signal and is often masked underneath that signal. Spurious tones are any tones other than a [[fundamental tone]] or its [[harmonics]].<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/62jmxDQR8 Definition of spurious tones]</ref> They also include tones generated within the back-to-back connected transmit and receive terminal or [[Channel service unit|channel units]], when the fundamental is applied to the transmit terminal or channel-unit input.
